messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /consumer/subscribe

- All HTTP methods acceptable (overrides individual method results):
  true

  true

- TRACE acceptable:
  true

- GET acceptable:
  true

- PUT acceptable:
  true

- DELETE acceptable:
  true

- PATCH acceptable:

Explanation:
- The subscribe handler is declared as:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/subscribe", produces = "text/event-stream")
  public ResponseEntity<SseEmitter> subscribe(WebRequest request) { ... }
  Because there is no class-level @RequestMapping on the controller, the full request path is exactly "/consumer/subscribe".
- In Spring MVC, @RequestMapping without a method attribute does not restrict HTTP methods â€” it matches requests regardless of HTTP method. Therefore, based on the code, all HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE) are acceptable. The "all HTTP methods acceptable" flag is set to true and thus overrides individual method flags.
- Note: produces = "text/event-stream" affects content type negotiation but does not restrict the HTTP method.
